enance-child-support-agency\" title=\"child maintenance\">child maintenance</a></li>\n  <li>set up a <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/deduction-from-earnings-order-deo\" title=\"deduction from earnings order\">deduction from earnings order</a> (<abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>)</li>\n  <li>answer enquiries from organisations used by the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> to collect payments of child maintenance on their behalf</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Your legal obligations when deducting child maintenance</h2>\n\n<p>By law, you must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>give information to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> when requested </li>\n  <li>send payments to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> as soon as possible, but no later than the 19th day of the month following the month you took it </li>\n  <li>let the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> know immediately if there are any problems with taking payments from a paying parent&rsquo;s earnings</li>\n  <li>make regular payments - if you don&rsquo;t send payments to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> and don&rsquo;t tell them why, they can take you to court </li>\n  <li>tell the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> in writing within 10 days of an employee leaving your business </li>\n  <li>tell the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> in writing within 10 days if they ask you to set up a deductions from earnings order (<abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>) for someone who doesn&rsquo;t work for you </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The ‘paying parent’ is the parent the child doesn’t live with.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/deduction-from-earnings-order-deo","slug":"deduction-from-earnings-order-deo","order":2,"title":"Deduction from earnings order (DEO)","body":"<p>This is a way of collecting <a href=\"/arranging-child-maintenance-child-support-agency\" title=\"child maintenance\">child maintenance</a> directly from a paying parent’s earnings or pension.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The ‘paying parent’ is the parent the child doesn’t live with.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>The Child Support Agency (<abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr>), or an authorised debt collection agency, will send you a deduction from earnings order (<abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>) if one of your employees is a paying parent who:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>chooses to pay child maintenance direct from their earnings</li>\n  <li>doesn’t pay the correct amount of child maintenance on time</li>\n  <li>doesn’t pay at all</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must deduct the amount of child maintenance stated on the <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> from your employee’s <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/what-the-child-support-agency-counts-as-earnings\" title=\"net earnings\">net earnings</a> or their pension and <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/making-payments-to-the-child-support-agency\" title=\"pay it to the CSA\">pay it to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr></a>. This will include any arrears that may be due.</p>\n\n<h2>If you get more than one <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> for an employee</h2>\n\n<p>You could get more than one <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> if your employee is paying maintenance for children by different &lsquo;receiving parents&rsquo;. You need to make a payment for each <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The ‘receiving parent’ is the parent or carer the child lives with.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Other court orders against your employee</h2>\n\n<p>You could get a <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> from the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> and an attachment of earnings order (<abbr title=\"attachment of earnings order\">AEO</abbr>) from a court. </p>\n\n<p><abbr title=\"attachment of earnings orders\">AEOs</abbr> work in a similar way to <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings orders\">DEOs</abbr>, but there are rules about which money you should take first.</p>\n\n<p>You can download a leaflet that tells you more about <abbr title=\"attachment of earnings orders\">AEOs</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://hmctscourtfinder.justice.gov.uk/courtfinder/forms/ae-handbook-eng.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Attachment Orders: A guide for employers' (PDF, 730KB\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Attachment Orders: A guide for employers’ (PDF, 730KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/how-deduction-from-earnings-orders-work","slug":"how-deduction-from-earnings-orders-work","order":3,"title":"How deduction from earnings orders work","body":"<p>The <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/deduction-from-earnings-order-deo\" title=\"deduction from earnings order\">deduction from earnings order</a> (<abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>) will give you information you need to make deductions, including:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    <p>the <strong>normal deduction rate</strong> (<abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr>) - the amount of <a href=\"/arranging-child-maintenance-child-support-agency\" title=\"child maintenance\">child maintenance</a> the Child Support Agency (<abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr>) takes from your employee&rsquo;s <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/what-the-child-support-agency-counts-as-earnings\" title=\"net earnings\">net earnings</a> in each pay period</p>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <p>the <strong>protected earnings rate</strong> (<abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr>) or <strong>protected earnings proportion</strong> (<abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr>) - the amount your employee needs to keep to pay for their own living costs</p>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <p>the date the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> expects you to start making deductions</p>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <p>how often you should <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/making-payments-to-the-child-support-agency\" title=\"make payments\">make payments</a></p>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> applies to cases opened before 3 March 2003. The <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> applies to cases opened from 3 March 2003.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example - deducting the full <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr>:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Your employee’s net earnings are £160 a week.</p>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> is £30 a week and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> is £100 a week.</p>\n\n<p>Net earnings minus the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> of £100 = £60, so you&rsquo;d send the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> the full <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> of £30.</p>\n\n<p>You can deduct up to £1 for administration costs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you can&rsquo;t make a full deduction</h2>\n\n<p>You must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>keep a record of the shortfall (the difference between the net earnings and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> or <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr>)</li>\n  <li>carry forward the shortfall to the next period</li>\n  <li>send the deduction, if there is one, to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You then deduct the full amount of the shortfall plus the <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> the next pay period. You must still leave your employee with the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> or <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr>.</p>\n\n<p>If the shortfall is carried forward for several weeks before being repaid, keep a record of the ongoing shortfall.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example - where you can&rsquo;t take the full <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr>:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Your employee’s net earnings are £120 a week.</p>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> is £32 a week and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> is £96 a week.</p>\n\n<p>Net earnings minus the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> of £96 = £24, so you&rsquo;d send the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> £24. The shortfall of £8 is carried forward to the next pay period.</p>\n\n<p>You can deduct up to £1 for administration costs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>When you make deductions, you must make sure that you leave your employee with the amount of their <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> or <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> - unless the deduction is for administrative costs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you pay your employee holiday pay in advance</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll need to multiply the <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr> or <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> in line with the net earnings.</p>\n\n<p>This means if you double the net earnings because you’re paying 2 weeks instead of one, you’ll need to double the <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> or <abbr title=\"protected earnings rate\">PER</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example - including holiday pay in advance:</strong></p>\n\n<p>In this example, the earnings include 2 weeks&rsquo; holiday pay paid in advance.</p>\n\n<p>Your employee has net earnings of £160 a week. </p>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> is £32 a week and the <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> is £96 a week. </p>\n\n<p>Net earnings are £160 x 3 = £480 (1 week’s pay + 2 weeks&rsquo; holiday pay).</p>\n\n<p>Take away the <abbr title=\"protected earnings proportion\">PEP</abbr> of £96 x 3 (£288). This leaves £192, so you&rsquo;d send the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> the full <abbr title=\"normal deduction rate\">NDR</abbr> of £96 (£32 x 3).</p>\n\n<p>You can deduct up to £1 for administration costs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you get more than one <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> for an employee</h2>\n\n<p>Sometimes a paying parent has more than one case and is paying child maintenance for children by different receiving parents. </p>\n\n<p>The number of <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings orders\">DEOs</abbr> depends on when the cases were opened:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>for cases opened before 3 March 2003 - there will only ever be one <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> (you make one payment to the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> and it gets split later)</li>\n  <li>for cases opened after 3 March 2003 - you might get more than one <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> and need to make a payment for each</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The ‘paying parent’ is the parent the child doesn’t live with. The ‘receiving parent’ is the parent the child lives with.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/what-the-child-support-agency-counts-as-earnings","slug":"what-the-child-support-agency-counts-as-earnings","order":4,"title":"What the Child Support Agency counts as earnings","body":"<p>A <a href=\"/make-child-maintenance-deductions-employee-pay/deduction-from-earnings-order-deo\" title=\"deduction from earnings order\">deduction from earnings order</a> (<abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr>) can only be made from the following earnings:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>wages, fees, bonus, commission, overtime pay or any payments on top of wages</li>\n  <li>private or occupational pensions and compensation payments</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/statutory-sick-pay-ssp\" title=\"Statutory Sick Pay\">Statutory Sick Pay</a></li>\n  <li>contractual sick pay</li>\n  <li>contractual maternity pay</li>\n  <li>contractual paternity pay</li>\n  <li>contractual adoption pay</li>\n  <li>contractual redundancy pay</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Statutory pay is money that your employees are entitled to by law. Contractual pay is pay that you agree with your employees over and above statutory pay.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>What doesn&rsquo;t count as earnings for <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings orders\">DEOs</abbr></h2>\n\n<p>Your employee can&rsquo;t pay <a href=\"/arranging-child-maintenance-child-support-agency\" title=\"child maintenance\">child maintenance</a> by <abbr title=\"deduction from earnings order\">DEO</abbr> if their only earnings are in the following categories:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>amounts paid by a public department of the Government of Northern Ireland or any country outside the UK</li>\n  <li>any social security pension, allowance or benefit</li>\n  <li>tax credits</li>\n  <li>any pension or allowance paid for disability</li>\n  <li>guaranteed minimum pension within the Social Security Pensions Act 1975</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/statutory-maternity-pay\" title=\"Statutory Maternity Pay\">Statutory Maternity Pay</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/ordinary-statutory-paternity-pay\" title=\"Statutory Paternity Pay\">Statutory Paternity Pay</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/statutory-adoption-pay\" title=\"Statutory Adoption Pay\">Statut