one gets paid, you still need to work out their equivalent hourly rate to see if they&rsquo;re getting the minimum wage.</p>\n\n<p>There are 4 different ways of doing this for workers:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-by-the-hour\" title=\"paid by the hour\">paid by the hour</a> (known as &lsquo;time work&rsquo;)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-an-annual-salary\" title=\"paid an annual salary\">paid an annual salary</a>, under a contract for a basic number of hours each year (known as &lsquo;salaried hours&rsquo;)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-per-task-or-piece-of-work-done\" title=\"paid by the piece\">paid by the piece</a> &ndash; the number of things they make, or tasks they complete (known as &lsquo;output work&rsquo;)</li>\n  <li><a href=\"/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-in-other-ways-unmeasured-work\" title=\"paid in other ways\">paid in other ways</a> (known as &lsquo;unmeasured work&rsquo;)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can then use the <a href=\"/am-i-getting-minimum-wage\" title=\"National Minimum Wage calculator\">National Minimum Wage calculator</a> to check if payments are over the minimum wage.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>What counts as working time</h2>\n\n<p>For all types of work, include time spent:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>at work and required to be working, or on standby near the workplace (but don&rsquo;t include rest breaks)</li>\n  <li>not working because of machine breakdown, but kept at the workplace</li>\n  <li>travelling on business</li>\n  <li>training or travelling to training during normal working hours</li>\n  <li>working during a time when workers are allowed to sleep, if the employer provides a place to sleep</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Don&rsquo;t include time spent:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>travelling between home and work</li>\n  <li>away from work on rest breaks, holidays, sick leave or maternity leave</li>\n  <li>away from work because of industrial action</li>\n  <li>at the workplace but not working during a time when workers are allowed to sleep (if you provide a place to sleep)</li>\n</ul>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-by-the-hour","slug":"paid-by-the-hour","order":2,"title":"Paid by the hour","body":"<p>Workers paid according to the number of hours they are at work are classed as doing &lsquo;time work&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>For these workers, the average hourly pay has to be at least the National Minimum Wage, worked out over the period each pay packet covers - so for a worker who gets paid once a month, this period will be 1 month.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example:</strong><br />\nWorkers in a call centre are paid for the number of hours they work each month.</p>\n\n<p>Alan works in the call centre. He is 23 and is eligible for the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">minimum wage rate</a> of £6.19. He works a total of 140 hours during the month of January.</p>\n\n<p>This means he must be paid at least £866.60 for this month&rsquo;s work (£6.19 multiplied by 140).</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Use the <a href=\"/am-i-getting-minimum-wage\" title=\"National Minimum Wage calculator\">National Minimum Wage calculator</a> to check if payments are over the minimum wage.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-an-annual-salary","slug":"paid-an-annual-salary","order":3,"title":"Paid an annual salary","body":"<p>A worker is doing &lsquo;salaried hours&rsquo; work if they&rsquo;re paid:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a set basic number of hours each year under their contract</li>\n  <li>an annual salary in equal weekly or monthly amounts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Salaried hours workers&rsquo; contracts might not state the basic number of hours as an annual figure, but it must be possible to work this out. You can then use this figure to make sure the rate of pay is at least the minimum wage.</p>\n\n<h2>Work out the hourly rate</h2>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Find the basic annual hours in the worker’s contract.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide this by the number of times they get paid each year (eg 12 if they get paid monthly) - this gives you the average number of hours covered by each pay packet.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide the amount they get in each pay packet by this number. This gives you the worker’s hourly rate.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nJeba&rsquo;s contract says she must work 2,040 hours each year.</p>\n\n<p>She&rsquo;s eligible for the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">minimum wage rate</a> of £6.19.</p>\n\n<p>She gets paid monthly (12 times a year), so each pay packet covers an average of 170 hours (2,040 divided by 12).</p>\n\n<p>This means she must be paid at least £1,052.30 a month (£1,052.30 divided by 170 makes £6.19) for the basic hours in her contract.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Use the <a href=\"/am-i-getting-minimum-wage\" title=\"National Minimum Wage calculator\">National Minimum Wage calculator</a> to find out if a salaried hours worker is being paid the minimum wage.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-per-task-or-piece-of-work-done","slug":"paid-per-task-or-piece-of-work-done","order":4,"title":"Paid per task or piece of work done","body":"<p>Workers paid per task they perform or piece of work they do (eg piece work) are classed as doing &lsquo;output work&rsquo;. They must be paid either at least the minimum wage for every hour worked or on the basis of a &lsquo;fair rate&rsquo; for each task or piece of work they do.</p>\n\n<h2>Fair rate</h2>\n\n<p>The fair rate is the amount that allows an average worker to be paid the minimum wage per hour if they work at an average rate.</p>\n\n<p>There is a way to work out the fair rate per piece of work done which employers must follow.</p>\n\n<h2>Work out the fair rate</h2>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Find out the average rate of work per hour (tasks or pieces completed).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide it by 1.2 (this means new workers won’t be disadvantaged if they’re not as fast as the others yet).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide that number by the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">hourly minimum wage rate</a> to work out the fair rate for each piece of work completed.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>Work out the average rate of work per hour</h2>\n\n<p>To work out the rate to pay workers, employers must carry out a fair test to see what the average rate of work is.</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Test some or all of the workers. The group you test must be typical of the whole workforce - not just the most efficient or fastest ones.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Work out how many pieces of work have been completed in a normal, average working hour.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide this by the number of workers to work out the average rate.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If the work changes significantly, do another test to work out the new average rate. It’s not necessary to do another test if the same work is being done in a different environment, eg work previously done in a factory being done at home.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nWorkers are paid for each shirt they make. They can produce on average 12 shirts per hour. This number is divided by 1.2 to make 10.</p>\n\n<p>Andy is 21 and is eligible for the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">minimum wage rate</a> of £6.19.</p>\n\n<p>This means he must be paid at least 62p per shirt he makes (£6.19 divided by 10, rounded up).</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/paid-in-other-ways-unmeasured-work","slug":"paid-in-other-ways-unmeasured-work","order":5,"title":"Paid in other ways (unmeasured work)","body":"<p>If the work isn&rsquo;t covered by any of the other types of work, it&rsquo;s &lsquo;unmeasured work&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<p>Unmeasured work includes being paid a set amount to do a particular task, eg being paid £500 to lay a patio, regardless of how long it takes.</p>\n\n<p>To work out the minimum wage for unmeasured work, either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>record every hour worked and use the <a href=\"/am-i-getting-minimum-wage\" title=\"National Minimum Wage calculator\">National Minimum Wage calculator</a> to make sure the worker gets the minimum wage</li>\n  <li>make a &lsquo;daily average agreement of hours&rsquo;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Daily average agreement of hours</h2>\n\n<p>This is when the employer and worker agree a typical number of hours per day they expect to work on average. One agreement can cover several pay reference periods (eg weeks if the worker&rsquo;s paid weekly) if there&rsquo;s no change in the average number of hours.</p>\n\n<p>Daily average agreements of hours must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be agreed in writing</li>\n  <li>be made before the start of the pay reference period they cover</li>\n  <li>say how many hours the work should take each day (on average)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The employer must be able to prove that the number of hours worked on average is realistic.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nLouise is paid weekly and is 31. She&rsquo;s eligible for the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">minimum wage</a> of £6.19 an hour.</p>\n\n<p>In a particular week she&rsquo;s paid £120.</p>\n\n<p>Her agreed daily average number of hours is 5.</p>\n\n<p>In that week she worked for 4 days, so she&rsquo;s counted as having worked 20 hours that week (4 times 5).</p>\n\n<p>£120 divided by 20 hours gives a rate of £6 an hour. That&rsquo;s less than the National Minimum Wage.</p>\n</div>\